There's nothing like those approving nods you get while cruising in a classic car, but for those set on a more contemporary motoring feel while behind the wheel, stock classics can have their limitations. Sloppy steering, less than stellar acceleration and a loose, squeaky suspension often come to mind. This 1966 Mustang Restomod is an inspired combination of modern technology with old school motoring vibe, all wrapped in a unique and well-executed package that's sure to turn heads.

Ford's Lime Gold was a signature color for Mustangs of the late 60's and it's employed to great use in this inspired reimagining that adds a wide swath of black running from front to back over the scooped hood, hardtop and trunk all the way to the taillight panel against that nostalgic backdrop.  It's not just an eye-catching color scheme but it's also very well applied, with a smooth, glass-like finish from all angles. The chrome and trim all over - including the front and back bumpers, light bezels and window trim - all have an unblemished shine. Look closer up front and you'll see a set of fog lights hidden behind that new looking grille. Go around to the back and you'll see a set of clean chrome bezels surrounding the dual exhaust in the rear valance, a very cool finishing touch.

Once you look inside, the quality and inspired design of this interior are immediately obvious. There are some very cool touches here, as the color scheme of the exterior has been ably brought in: a primarily lime gold dash with black inserts is crowned by a new dashpad, and the lime gold door interiors surround matching black inserts of their own. Look in the back and you'll see another unique touch - the areas straddling the black back bench seat also carry that lime gold hue on their steel surfaces, unobscured by any quarter panel trim inside. The front black buckets and rear bench don't seem to have seen much use at all and their restored design has a very tasteful and comfortable look: aftermarket but very much right at home in this classic. Peer through the custom steering wheel and you'll see a set of aftermarket Dakota gauges fit seamlessly into the stock design of the instrument bezel - a combination of updated technology blended with a vintage look. There are also some great add-ons to improve the driving experience, including a chrome Ididit tilt column and a top-quality Rockford- Fosgate AM/FM system with iPod connectivity powering a set of speakers expertly installed in those front kick panels.

There's plenty of GO to match the SHOW here. A 347 stroker V8 engine sits as the foundation of the drivetrain and with its Crane Cam and MSD ignition, it's sure to provide all the power you could want. It's paired to a C4 3 speed transmission with highway-friendly 3.08 gears in the back. A generously-sized aluminum radiator sits in front to keep temperatures down and a billet serpentine pulley system adds yet another visual element to a nice clean compartment that features more than its share of them. The addition of a state of the art power rack and pinion steering is a HUGE upgrade over the steering box that came stock in Mustangs of this era, eliminating the slop that was part and parcel of the old design, and the constant need to correct that came with it for a much more precise feel. This Mustang sits on a set of American Racing Wheels with Shelby knockoffs, wrapped in performance radials.

The added gloss and shine are the perfect complement to the mirror-like new chrome bumpers, complete trim, and shiny Cragar SS wheels that are as much an iconic as the Mustang.  Plus, the black vinyl roof is a great period-correct premium touch.

That standout roof is also a great introduction to the interior color.  You can tell there was the right investments in keeping the dash, door panels, headliner, and comfort-weave bucket seats looking dark and fresh.  But this is not a full midnight package.  You've got great brightwork on everything from the newer door handles to the factory center console.  Plus, all your favorite pieces have plenty of shine like the classic sports steering wheel, heat/defrost controls, and the correct round five-gauge full readout panel.  And because this is the perfect cool cruising classic, they made sure you could listen to your favorite tunes on the upgraded Kenwood AM/FM/CD stereo system.

When you open the hood, you'll see all the right pieces for a great driving classic.  Ford's trusty 289 V8 looks great with serious signs of keeping it reliable.  The clean presentation showcases the MSD ignition as well as fresh belts, wires, and hoses.  Plus, a Griffin aluminum radiator is always a welcomed upgrade.  But as you marvel at the right reliable components, don't forget to also spot the performance upgrades.  This V8 inhales deeply with a four-barrel carburetor, and it exhales with authority through headers that feed the stainless dual exhaust.  This is the kind of car that wants you to feel the road, and this cruising attitude Is heightened by the three-speed automatic transmission and front disc brakes.  So you'll love driving this classic near or far.

Complete with owner's manual and a restoration photo book, you are looking at an American icon that is distinctive for being both premium and great to drive.  A total package classic at a value price never waits for long, so don't miss out.  Call today!!!

CLASSIC CAR RESTORATIONS:

The term "restoration" in context to the vintage car world has taken on a definition of its own. For some people, a restoration is simply painting a car and replacing items as needed, while for others, restoration means an extensive disassembly and overhaul, with each piece getting rebuilt or replaced.

As a consumer, it's important to understand the basics of restoration levels for it can impact classic car values substantially. There are hundreds of ways to “restore” a vintage car or truck including but not limited to the following: i).
Frame off restoration.
Body of vehicle is completely taken off the frame and restoration includes body, frame, floor pans (top and bottom), etc. these restorations tend to be extensive and costly. ii).
Rotisserie restoration.

These restorations are when the body (or body and frame on a unibody vehicle) are disassembled and restored utilizing a rotisserie. Body of vehicle is completely taken off the frame and restoration includes body, frame, floor pans (top and bottom), etc. these restorations tend to be extensive and costly and iii).
Cosmetic or “driver quality” restoration.

These restoration are typically limited to cosmetic items including paint and body, interior, trim and emblems, etc. Within the three levels or restoration mentioned above, there can be varying quality from an “in the garage / amateur” restoration to a high dollar professional “concours” restoration. There is a universal 100 point grading system rating classic car conditions ranging from 100 being excellent to 20 being unrestorable.
In addition to the levels of restoration above, it's important to understand the type of restoration as well for it can also impact value substantially. Type of restorations include: i).
Factory or stock restoration.

This type of restoration is geared towards restoring the car or truck to stock specs from the factory as if it were new. These types of restorations use original or oem (original equipment manufacturer) where possible. Factory original restorations tend to bring the highest dollars from collectors. ii).
Custom restoration.

These types of restorations are geared towards builder preference over factory stock. These can be refereed to as “customs” or “hot rods”. Typically these vehicles will have custom paint work, aftermarket wheels, suspension upgrades, power plant transplants, etc. A specific sector of custom restoration vehicles is “pro-touring” or “restomod / restomods” which are custom built with a more modern street performance and creature comforts than the original factory vehicle.
Please note that WWVA is not a restoration shop nor do we restore vehicles to any degree.

This is the one.  This candy apple red 1966 Mustang 289, automatic convertible is at home in a show, museum or with the top down on an open road.  One owner since 1974.  Driven daily until it was completely disassembled, rebuilt and restored.  The complete restoration was from the frame rails up including the drive train and suspension.  See it on Mustang Restorations "customers' mustangs" page 3 (Evo's '66 Convertible).  While the engine was apart it received an Edelbrock 4 barrel, manifold, matching cam and dual exhausts.  This increased the performance and reliability without changing the pure stock looks.  Body panels were replaced rather than repaired.  I believe Doc and his crew lavished more work and expertise on this car than Ford did when it was built, and it shows.  This car has not seen a drop of rain since it was rebuilt.  She is 51 and she still turns heads.  Because I know the cost of the restoration and the work that went into it I do not take it out and enjoy it as I should.  It is time to let it go to someone who will take it out and enjoy it.  I would call this car mint, except that it has never been scored in a concourse event.
